{
  "doc_id": "55897",
  "text": "Regarding chronic morphine effects, DOR knockout mice showed enhanced sensitization to locomotor effects of morphine , and pharmacological blockade of DOR by NTI or naltriben (Billa et al., 2010) increased morphine-induced locomotor sensitization. Notably, morphine acts at mu opioid receptors in vivo [CITATION_1] and does not directly activate DORs, as suggested by intact morphine analgesia (Y. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ) and reward (Table 3) in DOR knockout mice. Therefore the exact nature of delta-mu opioid receptor interactions in vivo and mechanisms underlying DOR-regulated chronic morphine effects remain to be clarified.",
